\chapter{Decoding the Transcriptional Control of miRNAs}
\label{chp:decoding-the-transcriptional-control-of}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Transcription start sites (TSSs) represent the precise genomic positions where RNA polymerase

II initiates transcription \cite{klooster2016substrat,liu2019predicti} . For miRNA genes, accurate TSS identification is fundamental to

understanding transcriptional regulation because TSSs anchor the promoter regions where

transcription factors (TFs) bind to control gene expression \cite{lee2004microrna} . Without knowing where

transcription begins, mapping of TF binding sites to functional regulatory elements remains

imprecise. Therefore, TSS annotation serves as the prerequisite for constructing comprehensive

TF-miRNA regulatory networks and represents the essential first step toward understanding why

specific miRNAs become dysregulated in disease states. The genomic organization of miRNA

genes presents unique challenges for TSS identification \cite{lee2003nuclear} . Approximately 50% of human

miRNAs are intragenic, located within introns of protein-coding host genes and potentially

sharing transcriptional control with their hosts. The remaining miRNAs are intergenic,

possessing independent promoters that can be located tens to hundreds of kilobases upstream

from the mature miRNA sequence \cite{georgaki2014microtss} . This architectural diversity means that a single TSS

prediction strategy cannot be universally applied, and context-specific approaches are required

to accurately annotate the transcriptional origins of different miRNA classes.

Existing approaches for miRNA TSS prediction face significant limitations. Experimental

methods such as CAGE-seq, while effective for protein-coding genes, have reduced sensitivity

for miRNAs due to the relatively low expression levels of primary miRNA transcripts \cite{shiraki2003gene} .

Computational methods relying on sequence motifs or single data types suffer from high false-

positive rates when applied to the diverse genomic contexts of miRNA genes \cite{suzuki2002dbtss} . Previous

machine learning approaches trained on limited datasets lack generalization capability across

different cell types and species. These limitations have resulted in incomplete and inconsistent

TSS annotations across available databases, hindering systematic analysis of miRNA

transcriptional regulation.


This chapter aims to address the incomplete annotation of miRNA upstream regulation by

developing a comprehensive computational platform for TSS prediction and TF-miRNA

interaction mapping. Specifically, we pursue three objectives: first, to develop a deep learning

model that integrates multi-modal genomic evidence for accurate TSS prediction; second, to

systematically annotate TSSs and TF binding sites across human and mouse miRNomes; and

third, to construct an accessible web resource that enables researchers to explore miRNA

upstream regulation. By establishing this data foundation, we enable the network analyses

pursued in subsequent chapters of this thesis.


\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}


\subsection{Data Collection and Integration}
\label{sec:data-collection-and-integration}

We integrated five distinct types of high-throughput sequencing data to capture complementary

signals associated with transcription initiation. CAGE-seq and TSS-seq provide direct evidence

of transcription start sites through capture of 5'-capped RNA molecules. ChIP-seq data for

H3K4me3 histone modification and RNA Polymerase II occupancy mark active promoter

regions. DNase-seq identifies regions of open chromatin accessibility that are permissive for

transcription factor binding. This multi-modal approach ensures that TSS predictions are

supported by convergent evidence from orthogonal experimental techniques.

In this major update, miRStart 2.0 integrates a high-resolution deep learning-based signal

classification model with extensive gene transcription data from leading databases such as

FANTOM \cite{consorti2014promoter} , DBTSS \cite{suzuki2018dbtss} , and ENCODE \cite{luo2020developm} . We aggregated over 4,500 high-throughput

sequencing datasets from major genomic consortia and public repositories. The FANTOM5

consortium provided extensive CAGE-seq data across hundreds of human and mouse cell types

and tissues. The ENCODE project contributed ChIP-seq and DNase-seq data with standardized

quality control. Additional datasets were retrieved from the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO) to

maximize coverage across biological conditions. All datasets were processed through uniform

quality control pipelines to ensure consistency and comparability.


\subsection{Deep Learning Model Architecture}
\label{sec:deep-learning-model-architecture}

The miRStart 2.0 model employs a multi-modal feature integration strategy that combines

signals from all five data types into a unified predictive framework. For each candidate genomic

region, sequencing read densities from each data type were extracted and normalized across a

standardized window surrounding potential TSSs. These multi-dimensional features were

concatenated into input matrices that preserve both the signal intensity and positional

relationships of different genomic marks, enabling the model to learn complex patterns of co-

occurrence that distinguish true TSSs from background. We designed a convolutional neural

network (CNN) architecture optimized for recognizing spatial patterns in genomic signal data.

The network comprises two convolutional layers for feature extraction, followed by three fully

connected layers for classification. Convolutional filters were designed to capture both local

signal peaks and broader regional patterns characteristic of promoter architecture. Dropout

regularization and batch normalization were incorporated to prevent overfitting and improve

generalization. The model outputs a probability score indicating the likelihood that a given

position represents a true TSS.

The model was trained on approximately 60,000 experimentally validated TSSs derived from

the DataBase of Transcriptional Start Sites (DBTSS) and ENCODE database. Positive training

examples were centered on validated TSSs, while negative examples were sampled from

genomic regions lacking transcription initiation signals. The dataset was split into training

(70%), validation (15%), and test (15%) sets with stratification to ensure balanced representation.

Model performance was evaluated using standard classification metrics including accuracy,

precision, recall, and area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC-ROC).


\subsection{TSS Annotation Pipeline}
\label{sec:tss-annotation-pipeline}

The trained model was applied to systematically scan upstream regions of all annotated pre-

miRNAs in the human and mouse genomes. For each miRNA, we examined the region

extending 100 kilobases upstream of the pre-miRNA sequence. Genomic positions where the

model prediction score exceeded a threshold of 0.7 were flagged as putative TSSs. For miRNAs


with multiple high-scoring positions, all candidates were retained to capture alternative promoter

usage. The resulting annotations include TSS coordinates, prediction confidence scores, and

tissue specificity profiles based on the underlying sequencing data support.


\subsection{TF-miRNA Interaction Mapping}
\label{sec:tf-mirna-interaction-mapping}

With TSS positions established, we mapped transcription factor binding sites to functional

promoter regions. We defined promoter windows extending 10,000 base pairs upstream to 1,000

base pairs downstream of each annotated TSS. TF binding sites within these windows were

identified by integrating ChIP-seq peak calls from ENCODE and other sources, filtered for those

with supporting DNase-seq accessibility evidence. Conservation scores from UCSC were

incorporated to prioritize evolutionarily constrained binding sites. This approach yielded tissue-

specific TF-miRNA interaction networks reflecting the regulatory relationships controlling

miRNA expression.


\subsection{Web Database Development}
\label{sec:web-database-development}

We developed the miRStart 2.0 web database to provide community access to our annotations

and analysis tools. The database features an interactive genome browser enabling visualization

of TSS predictions alongside supporting sequencing tracks. Users can filter results by tissue type,

conservation level, and prediction confidence. TF-miRNA interaction networks are presented

through interactive visualizations with links to external resources for detailed TF information.

The database also provides downloadable datasets and programmatic access through a REST

API, facilitating integration with downstream analysis pipelines.


