\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}


\subsection{Performance Benchmarking Against Existing Tools}
\label{sec:performance-benchmarking-against-existin}

We benchmarked miRStart 2.0 against existing miRNA TSS prediction methods using an

independent test dataset of 2,000 validated TSSs not included in model training. MiRStart 2.0

consistently outperformed competing methods across all evaluation metrics for both human and

mouse datasets. The model achieved an AUC-ROC exceeding 0.92, with balanced precision and

recall indicating robust discrimination between true TSSs and background positions.

Performance advantages were particularly pronounced for intergenic miRNAs, where existing


methods showed reduced accuracy due to the variable distance between TSSs and mature

miRNA sequences.


\subsection{Validation with Experimentally Verified TSSs}
\label{sec:validation-with-experimentally-verified}

We validated model predictions against a curated set of 24 miRNAs with experimentally

determined TSSs from multiple independent studies. These non-cell-specific validations

represent TSSs that are consistently used across diverse cellular contexts. Our predictions

achieved 83.3% exact positional match (0 base pair distance) with the experimentally validated

TSSs, with the remaining predictions falling within 500 base pairs of validated positions. This

high concordance demonstrates that miRStart 2.0 achieves the resolution necessary for accurate

promoter delineation. We further validated predictions against 61 miRNA TSSs specifically

characterized in human embryonic stem cells (hESCs), representing cell-type-specific promoter

usage. For these more challenging cases, our model achieved 93.4% exact positional match with

validated TSSs. The improved performance on cell-type-specific TSSs likely reflects the rich

hESC representation in our training data from ENCODE. These results demonstrate that

miRStart 2.0 can accurately identify context-dependent TSS usage when appropriate training

data are available.


