This chapter established the data foundation essential for subsequent analyses in this thesis. By


developing miRStart 2.0, we addressed the critical gap of incomplete miRNA TSS annotation,

enabling accurate mapping of upstream transcriptional control. The comprehensive TF-miRNA

regulatory atlas provides the input layer of the miRNA regulatory network, complementing the

well-characterized downstream target interactions. The methodological paradigm of data

integration and deep learning prediction established here provides a template for addressing

similar annotation challenges across regulatory genomics. Several limitations warrant

consideration. Model performance depends on the availability and quality of training data,

potentially limiting accuracy for cell types or species underrepresented in current datasets.

Predictions represent computational estimates that require experimental validation for individual

applications. The current pipeline does not distinguish between active and poised promoters,

which would require integration of RNA-seq data. Future development will incorporate

emerging single-cell ATAC-seq data to enable cell-type-specific predictions at unprecedented

resolution, and expansion to additional species will broaden the utility of this resource.

